export const notes = "\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>1. Distribution and Overview</h3>\n  <p>Mangroves are salt-tolerant forests found in tropical and subtropical coastal regions between <strong>30°N and 30°S</strong>.</p>\n  <p><strong>Where they grow:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Intertidal zones — the area between high tide and low tide marks</li>\n    <li>Sheltered coastlines protected from strong wave action</li>\n    <li>Estuaries (where rivers meet the sea) and river deltas</li>\n  </ul>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Global extent:</strong> ~136,000 km² worldwide<br>\n    <strong>Southeast Asia:</strong> ~35.6% of the world's mangroves — the largest regional concentration on Earth<br>\n    <strong>Indonesia:</strong> ~23,000 km² — the single largest national mangrove area\n  </div>\n  <p><strong>Other major mangrove nations:</strong> Brazil, Nigeria, Australia, Mexico</p>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Singapore:</strong> Over 35 species of mangrove trees — exceptional diversity for such a small country\n  </div>\n  <p><strong>Conditions required for mangroves:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Saline or brackish water (can tolerate salt)</li>\n    <li>Warm temperatures above 20°C year-round</li>\n    <li>Muddy or silty substrate (fine sediment)</li>\n    <li>Sheltered location protected from strong waves and currents</li>\n  </ul>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>2. Horizontal Zonation</h3>\n  <p>Mangroves are arranged in <strong>distinct zones</strong> from the sea towards land, based on how often each zone is flooded by tides and the salinity level. Each species is adapted to a specific zone.</p>\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Pioneer / Seaward Zone</h4>\n      <p><strong>Position:</strong> Most seaward, permanently waterlogged</p>\n      <p><strong>Species:</strong> Avicennia (sea purslane), Sonneratia</p>\n      <p><strong>Flooding:</strong> Almost constantly flooded</p>\n      <p><strong>Key feature:</strong> Pneumatophores (pencil roots) projecting above mud</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Middle Zone</h4>\n      <p><strong>Position:</strong> Between seaward and landward zones</p>\n      <p><strong>Species:</strong> Rhizophora (mangrove proper)</p>\n      <p><strong>Flooding:</strong> Regular tidal flooding</p>\n      <p><strong>Key feature:</strong> Distinctive prop/stilt roots arching above water</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Landward Zone</h4>\n      <p><strong>Position:</strong> Closest to land</p>\n      <p><strong>Species:</strong> Bruguiera (black mangrove), Xylocarpus</p>\n      <p><strong>Flooding:</strong> Only flooded at high tide</p>\n      <p><strong>Key feature:</strong> Knee-bend roots (pneumatophores looping above mud)</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Terrestrial Fringe</h4>\n      <p><strong>Position:</strong> Transition zone to land</p>\n      <p><strong>Species:</strong> Nypa palm, Acanthus</p>\n      <p><strong>Flooding:</strong> Rarely flooded (only extreme high tides)</p>\n      <p><strong>Key feature:</strong> Mixed species; transition to terrestrial vegetation</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam tip:</strong> Remember — zonation occurs because each species is adapted to a different flooding duration and salinity level. Seaward species tolerate the most flooding; landward species tolerate the least.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>3. Root Adaptations</h3>\n  <p>Mangroves grow in <strong>waterlogged, anaerobic</strong> (oxygen-poor) soil. Roots cannot obtain oxygen from the soil, so special adaptations are needed for gas exchange.</p>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>1. Pneumatophores (pencil/peg roots) — Avicennia, Sonneratia</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Vertical roots that grow upward and project above the mud surface like pencils</li>\n      <li>Have <strong>lenticels</strong> — tiny pores on the root surface</li>\n      <li>Lenticels absorb atmospheric oxygen directly from the air</li>\n      <li>Allow root cells to respire aerobically even in anaerobic waterlogged soil</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>2. Prop / Stilt Roots (arching aerial roots) — Rhizophora</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Curved aerial roots that arc from the trunk down into the mud</li>\n      <li>Provide structural stability in soft, shifting, waterlogged mud</li>\n      <li>Also bear lenticels for gas exchange above water level</li>\n      <li>Create a complex root framework that traps sediment and organic matter</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>3. Knee-bend Roots (knee roots) — Bruguiera</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Roots that loop upward above the mud surface and then curve back down</li>\n      <li>Lenticels on the exposed upper portion absorb oxygen</li>\n      <li>Allow respiration in the landward zone which is flooded less frequently</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>4. Plank / Buttress Roots — some large species</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Flange-like roots extending outward from the base of the trunk</li>\n      <li>Provide extra structural support, similar to buttress roots of rainforest emergent trees</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam tip:</strong> Always explain WHY the adaptation helps. For pneumatophores: \"The vertical roots project above the mud. Lenticels on their surface absorb oxygen from the air, allowing the roots to respire in the oxygen-poor waterlogged soil.\"\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>4. Salt Adaptations</h3>\n  <p>Seawater has a much higher salt concentration than plant cells. Without adaptations, osmosis would cause water to leave plant cells, killing the plant. Mangroves have evolved four main strategies:</p>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>1. Salt Exclusion (Ultrafiltration) — Rhizophora</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Root cell membranes act as a semi-permeable ultrafiltration system</li>\n      <li>Over <strong>90% of Na⁺ (sodium) ions</strong> are blocked at the root surface</li>\n      <li>Water is absorbed but most salt is excluded — the most effective strategy</li>\n      <li>Salt never enters the plant</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>2. Salt Secretion / Excretion — Avicennia, Aegiceras</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Specialised <strong>salt glands</strong> on leaf surfaces actively pump salt out</li>\n      <li>Salt appears as white crystals on leaves; washed away by rain</li>\n      <li>Energy-costly but effective for managing salt that does enter the plant</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>3. Salt Accumulation in Leaves — Xylocarpus</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Salt is stored in ageing leaves rather than in vital tissues</li>\n      <li>When the old leaves drop and decay away from the tree, salt is removed with them</li>\n      <li>Known as the \"sacrificial leaf\" strategy</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>4. Succulence — some species</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Leaves are thick and fleshy, storing large amounts of water</li>\n      <li>Extra water dilutes the salt concentration within leaf cells</li>\n      <li>Reduces the effective salt concentration to tolerable levels</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>5. Vivipary (On-Tree Seed Germination)</h3>\n  <p><strong>Vivipary</strong> is the germination of seeds while they are still attached to the parent tree. This is unique to mangroves among all tree species — an extraordinary adaptation to the harsh intertidal environment.</p>\n\n  <p><strong>Process:</strong></p>\n  <ol>\n    <li>Fruit/seed develops on the parent tree</li>\n    <li>Seed germinates and grows into a seedling (<strong>propagule</strong>) while still attached to the branch</li>\n    <li>The developed propagule eventually drops from the tree</li>\n    <li>It floats on the water and disperses, often travelling great distances</li>\n    <li>When it reaches suitable mud, it anchors and continues to grow</li>\n  </ol>\n\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Rhizophora propagule</h4>\n      <p>Long, torpedo-shaped — up to <strong>60 cm</strong> in length. Designed to spear into mud on contact and anchor immediately.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Avicennia propagule</h4>\n      <p>Small and highly buoyant — can float for <strong>up to one year</strong>, allowing dispersal across vast ocean distances.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h4>Bruguiera propagule</h4>\n      <p>Cigar-shaped. Intermediate in size between Rhizophora and Avicennia propagules.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Key advantage:</strong> The seedling is already partially developed when it leaves the parent tree — far higher survival rate in the harsh intertidal environment compared to ungerminated seeds.<br>\n    Propagules can float for thousands of kilometres, which explains the wide geographic distribution of many mangrove species.\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam tip:</strong> Vivipary is a KEY exam topic. Be able to explain: (1) what it is, (2) why it is an advantage in the intertidal zone, and (3) how it aids dispersal.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>6. Environmental Functions</h3>\n  <p>Mangroves provide five critical ecological and protective functions:</p>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>1. Coastal Protection</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Dense prop root networks dissipate wave energy before it reaches the coast</li>\n      <li>Studies show mangroves reduce wave height by <strong>50–99%</strong></li>\n      <li>Protect shorelines from storms, erosion, and tsunami damage</li>\n    </ul>\n    <div class=\"case-study\">\n      <strong>2004 Indian Ocean Tsunami:</strong> Coastal villages sheltered behind intact mangrove forests suffered significantly less structural damage and fewer casualties than those on exposed shores.\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>2. Carbon Storage (Blue Carbon)</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Mangrove soils store approximately <strong>937 tonnes of carbon per hectare</strong> — among the highest of any ecosystem on Earth</li>\n      <li>\"Blue carbon\" refers to carbon stored by coastal ecosystems (mangroves, seagrasses, salt marshes) in waterlogged soil for millennia</li>\n      <li>Mangroves store <strong>3–5 times more carbon per unit area</strong> than tropical rainforests</li>\n      <li>Clearing mangroves releases this stored carbon, contributing significantly to climate change</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>3. Nursery Habitat for Marine Life</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Complex root systems provide shelter, breeding grounds, and feeding areas for juvenile fish and invertebrates</li>\n      <li>Approximately <strong>80% of commercially caught fish</strong> in tropical regions depend on mangroves at some life stage</li>\n      <li>Shrimps, crabs, and shellfish use mangroves as breeding grounds</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>4. Water Filtration</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Roots physically trap sediment, heavy metals, and agricultural chemicals as water flows from land to sea</li>\n      <li>Prevent excessive sedimentation of offshore coral reefs</li>\n      <li>Improve water quality in coastal areas</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <h4>5. Biodiversity Support</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Support a rich array of wildlife: kingfishers, herons, eagles (birds); estuarine crocodiles; monitor lizards; proboscis monkeys (Borneo); smooth-coated otters</li>\n      <li>Serve as critical stopover habitat for migratory birds</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>7. Singapore's Mangroves</h3>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Historical extent (1819):</strong> ~75 km² — covered large areas of Singapore's coast when Raffles arrived<br>\n    <strong>Current extent (2018):</strong> Only ~8.1 km² remains — approximately <strong>89% lost</strong> due to development and land reclamation\n  </div>\n\n  <p><strong>Main remaining mangrove sites:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve</strong> — Singapore's main mangrove reserve (202 hectares)</li>\n    <li><strong>Pasir Ris Park</strong> — accessible mangrove boardwalk</li>\n    <li><strong>Pulau Ubin</strong> — scattered patches throughout the island</li>\n    <li><strong>Chek Jawa Wetlands, Pulau Ubin</strong> — diverse coastal ecosystems including mangroves</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <h4>Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Designated an <strong>ASEAN Heritage Park in 2003</strong> — Singapore's only wetland ASEAN Heritage Park</li>\n      <li>Internationally important stopover for migratory birds on the <strong>East Asian–Australasian Flyway</strong></li>\n      <li>Wildlife: estuarine crocodiles, Malayan water monitors, smooth-coated otters, kingfishers</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <p><strong>Key threats to Singapore's mangroves:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Urban development and infrastructure expansion</li>\n    <li>Coastal reclamation (filling in sea and wetlands for land)</li>\n    <li>Intense land use pressure due to Singapore's small size and high population density</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <p><strong>Conservation efforts:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>NParks active restoration programmes</li>\n    <li>Artificial mangrove creation (e.g., Marina South)</li>\n    <li>Legal protection for remaining reserves</li>\n  </ul>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>8. Sundarbans — Global Case Study</h3>\n  <div class=\"case-study\">\n    <h4>Key Facts</h4>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Location:</strong> Ganges-Brahmaputra delta straddling Bangladesh and West Bengal, India</li>\n      <li><strong>Size:</strong> ~10,000 km² — the world's largest contiguous mangrove forest</li>\n      <li><strong>UNESCO World Heritage Site:</strong> designated 1987</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <p><strong>Biodiversity:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Royal Bengal Tiger</strong> (~400 individuals) — the Sundarbans is their last stronghold</li>\n    <li>Irrawaddy dolphins; saltwater crocodiles; spotted deer; numerous bird species</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <p><strong>Protective functions:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Absorbs storm surges from Bay of Bengal cyclones, protecting millions of people in Bangladesh and India</li>\n    <li><strong>1999 Super Cyclone:</strong> Areas behind intact mangroves suffered significantly less flooding</li>\n    <li><strong>2020 Cyclone Amphan:</strong> Sundarbans absorbed much of the storm's energy, substantially reducing inland damage</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <p><strong>Threats:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Sea level rise:</strong> Bangladesh is one of the most vulnerable countries globally; rising seas cause salinity intrusion and inundation</li>\n    <li>Increasing intensity of cyclones due to climate change</li>\n    <li>Fishing pressure, wood collection, and human encroachment</li>\n    <li>Bengal Tiger population under threat from habitat loss and human conflict</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam tip:</strong> For evaluation questions, consider both the importance of the Sundarbans AND the threats it faces. A strong answer will explain how climate change (sea level rise + stronger cyclones) threatens the very ecosystem that protects people from those same climate impacts.\n  </div>\n</div>\n";

